<docinfo partitionnum="3"><docinfo:dpsi id-string="05CC"/><docinfo:doc-heading>[456,130] FULLER v MURPHY</docinfo:doc-heading><docinfo:doc-id>UCPN_PRACDEC.SGM_UCPN.PRACDEC.456130</docinfo:doc-id><docinfo:doc-lang lang="en"/><docinfo:doc-country iso-cc="AU"/><docinfo:hier><docinfo:hierlev role="ancestor"><heading><title>PRACTICE DECISIONS</title></heading><docinfo:hierlev role="ancestor"><heading><title>PRACTICE DECISIONS</title></heading><docinfo:hierlev role="me"><heading><edpnum>[456,130]</edpnum><title>FULLER v MURPHY</title></heading></docinfo:hierlev></docinfo:hierlev></docinfo:hierlev></docinfo:hier><docinfo:bookseqnum>160050000</docinfo:bookseqnum><docinfo:lbu-meta><docinfo:metaitem name="lbu-sourcename" value="Ritchie's Uniform Civil Procedure NSW"/><docinfo:metaitem name="parent-docid" value="UCPN.PRACDEC"/><docinfo:metaitem name="parent-filename" value="pracdec.xml"/><docinfo:metaitem name="parent-docid" value="UCPN_PRACDEC.SGM_UCPN.PRACDEC.456130"/><docinfo:metaitem name="parent-filename" value="pracdec1010.xml"/></docinfo:lbu-meta><docinfo:selector>case</docinfo:selector><docinfo:load-date><date day="11" month="09" year="2012">11 September 2012</date></docinfo:load-date></docinfo>
<case:body><heading searchtype="PRACTICE-NOTE"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.PRACDEC.456130" type="ext"/>[456,130]</edpnum></heading>
<case:headnote>
<case:info><case:casename searchtype="PRACTICE-NOTE">FULLER v MURPHY</case:casename></case:info>
<case:info>
<case:courtinfo><case:courtname>Local Court, Downing Centre</case:courtname>
<case:judges><case:judge>Lulham M</case:judge>
</case:judges><case:dates><case:decisiondate>12 December 2003</case:decisiondate></case:dates>
<case:filenum>No 15376/00</case:filenum>
</case:courtinfo></case:info><catchwordgrp><catchwords><catchphrase>Application for rehearing of arbitration</catchphrase><catchphrase>Increase in prescribed amount from $3000 to $10,000 effected by Courts Legislation Amendment Act 1999</catchphrase><catchphrase>O'Keefe J not referred to transitional provisions effected by Sch 12 of the Courts Legislation Amendment Act 2000 when deciding Csalar v Circosta (2002) 55 NSWLR 212; [2002] NSWSC 482; BC200202888</catchphrase><catchphrase>Principles of stare decisis do not apply</catchphrase></catchwords>
</catchwordgrp></case:headnote><case:content>
<case:judgments><case:judgment><case:courtinfo><case:judges><case:judge>Lulham M</case:judge></case:judges></case:courtinfo>
<case:judgmentbody>
<p>
<text>In an identical factual situation to those in <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="2002"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr000040" spanref="cr000040-001"><ci:reporter value="NSWLR"/><ci:volume num="55"/><ci:page num="212"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr000041" spanref="cr000041-002"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC200202888"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Csalar v Circosta</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000040-001">(2002) 55 NSWLR 212</ci:span>; [2002] NSWSC 482; <ci:span spanid="cr000041-002"> BC200202888</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="346918" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> and <emph typestyle="it">Dear v Cassar</emph> (Local Court, Downing Centre, No 10491/02, Cloran M, 4 December 2002, unreported), Lulham M came to the opposite conclusion to Cloran M, holding that the principles of stare decisis do not apply as regards the Supreme Court decision in <emph typestyle="it">Csalar v Circosta</emph>,
<fnr fnrtoken="SMN.PRACDEC.190150.FTN1-R" fntoken="SMN.PRACDEC.190150.FTN1">1</fnr> above, since that decision is reasonably distinguishable from circumstances of the instant case, O'Keefe J was not having been referred to the relevant transitional provisions of the amending Act. In so doing, Lulham M said that he agreed with and adopted the submissions of paragraphs [10]&#x2013;[15] of the defendant's counsel's submissions as follows:</text></p>
<p>
<text>[10] His Honour Justice O'Keefe's decision was, with respect, based on the mistaken belief that there was no provision in the September 2000 amendment expressly stating that the amendments were not to affect matter already commenced as at the date of the amendment.</text></p>
<p>
<text>[11] The amending Act complies with the principle established in <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1957"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr000044" spanref="cr000044-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="CLR"/><ci:volume num="96"/><ci:page num="261"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr000045" spanref="cr000045-002" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="ALR"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1957"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="231"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Maxwell v Murphy</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000044-001" status="unval">(1957) 96 CLR 261</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr000045-002" status="unval">[1957] ALR 231</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="1423" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>:</text>
<blockquote>
<p>
<text>[T]he general rule of the common law is that a statute changing the law ought not, unless the intention appears with reasonable certainty, to be understood as applying to factual events that have already occurred in such a way as to confer or impose or otherwise affect rights or liabilities which the law had defined by reference to those past events.</text></p></blockquote></p>
<p>
<text>[12] The doctrine of stare decisis does not apply to the present matter. In <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1994"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr000046" spanref="cr000046-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="CLR"/><ci:volume num="181"/><ci:page num="18"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr000047" spanref="cr000047-002"><ci:reporter value="ALR"/><ci:volume num="121"/><ci:page num="153"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Re Tyler; Ex parte Foley</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000046-001" status="unval">(1994) 181 CLR 18</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr000047-002">121 ALR 153</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="60012" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>, the principle was described:</text>
<blockquote>
<p>
<text>[As operating] so that a court, bound by a previous decision whose ratio decidendi is not discernible, is bound to apply that decision when the circumstances of the instant case are not reasonably distinguishable from those which gave rise to the decision.</text></p></blockquote></p>
<p>
<text>[13] The circumstances of the present case are reasonably distinguishable from those which gave rise to the decision. We are aware of the proper intention of parliament when it passed the relevant amendment, that the amendments did not apply to matters already commenced. His Honour Justice O'Keefe was not. The <emph typestyle="it">circumstances</emph> in which he reached his decision are reasonably distinguishable.</text></p>
<p>
<text>[14] This court should not be bound by an appellate decision grounded upon a mistaken understanding, made in circumstances where the relevant section of the amending Act expressly stating that the amendments do not apply to matters already commenced was not brought to the attention of his Honour Justice O'Keefe.</text></p>
<p>
<text>[15] To disallow the defendant from proceeding with the application for re-hearing would be to contravene the true intention of parliament, in ensuring that the amendments passed in September 2000 did not apply to matters already commenced in the court.</text></p></case:judgmentbody></case:judgment>
